<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right; text-indent:14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">WWC0011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> by the Sutton Trust and the Education Endowment Foundation</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Key Points</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">The evidence suggests that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> white working class children in general perform more poorly than their peers and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">white working class boys </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">perform worse than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> other boys, white working class girls and boys from other ethnic communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">nearly one in seven secondary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">in 2012 saw </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pupils eligible for free school meals perform above the national average for all pupils in terms of capped GCSE points scores</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">Improved teaching, including strategies informed by evidence and effective evaluation, should be at the heart of any s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">trategies to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">improve boys’ achievement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> Teachers should learn more about using evidence in their initial training and professional development.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">The Education Endowment Foundation is currently testing the effectiveness of a range of programmes that could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">significantly improve teaching and attainment by white working class boys.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">Improved and increased apprenticeships with a strong work-based element must be provided to enable working class boys and girls to gain good jobs in the future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">The pupil premium sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">ould be more effectively used in schools, drawing on evidence of what works, and government should properly recognise those schools that make a difference with the premium</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">, with appropriate rewards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:14.2pt"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">About the Sutton Trust and the Education Endowment Found</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">ation</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Sutton Trust is a foundation set up in 1997, dedicated to improving social mobility through education. It has published over 135 research studies and funded and evaluated programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that have helped hundreds of thousands of young people of all ages, from early years through to Access to the Professions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Education Endowment Foundation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (EEF)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a charity set up in 2011 by the Sutton Trust as lead foundation in partnership with Impe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tus Trust, with a Department for Education grant of £125m. It is dedicated to breaking the link between family income and educational achievement. Since its launch the EEF has awarded £28.7 million to 56 projects working with over 300,000 pupils in over 1,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">800 schools across England.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 68.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The EEF’s mission is to break the link between family income and educational achievement, ensuring that underprivileged children can fulfill their potential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and make the most of their talents.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It aims to raise the attainment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">children facing disadvantage by:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Identifying promising educational innovations that address the needs of disadvantaged children;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Evaluating these innovations to extend and secure the evidence on what works and can be made to work at scale;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Encouraging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">schools, government, charities, and others to apply evidence and adopt innovations found to be effective.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">he extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TABLE 1: </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overall attainment of </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">white working class pupils</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> at Key Stage 2</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:418.2pt"><tr style="height:12.75pt"><td colspan="3" style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:418.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">% achieving Level 4 in English &amp; mathematics in Key Stage 2 </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">by ethnicity and FSM eligibility</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (2012</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> results</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:12.75pt"><td style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-styl