: Department for Education SFR04/2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">High performing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">schools and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">local authorities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nternal analysis has identified a wide variation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in pupil outcomes between schools with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> every </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">type</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> demographic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">intake</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> there were 428 secondary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– nearly one in seven - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where pupils eligible for free school meals perform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> above the national average for all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pupils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in te</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rms of capped GCSE points scores</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  These schools are spread across the spectrum of disadvantage and represent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of all schools, including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> schools of all types</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  At primary level there are 2568 schools (31% of all primaries) where the average proportion o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f FSM pupils achieving Level 4 in English and Maths exceeds the national average of all pupils.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The wide variance suggests that even schools with high proportions of white pupils from disadvantaged areas can make a difference to pupil outcomes and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> high performing schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may be an underused</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> resource which could be drawn upon to support lower performing schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> similar demographic “families”.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Likewise, at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority level there is wide variation in outcomes for pupils from disadvantaged ba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ckgrounds.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The London Challenge has improved outcomes in the capital, but Ofsted has pointed to greater challenges remaining in coastal towns and Northern cities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">The factors responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement, inclu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">ding the impact of home and family</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Sutton Trust and E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognise that a wide variety of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complex and interrelated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">factors affect the educational achievement of white pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This problem will not be solved sole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through the education system.  However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evidence presented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> above </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> education can play a central</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> role in break</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the link between family background and educational achievement, and both charities seek to contribute to this effort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.59pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Analy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sis by the Boston Consulting Group (BCG) for the Sutton Trust to help inform priorities for the EEF underlined the complex causes of the attainment gap. Their qualitative analysis found that teachers saw poor parental engagement as a crucial reason for wor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">king class underachievement. BCG identified a number of other potential causes of poor attainment among these pupils and students. Two-thirds of the teachers interviewed, particularly those teaching in primary schools, saw poor parental engagement as a key</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> factor. Teachers regarded poor standards of literacy are the biggest single factor leading to low attainment, with difficulties surrounding the transition between primary and secondary school also seen as very significant. Teachers also highlighted lack o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f engagement and aspiration among students as factors which led to poor behaviour and attainment.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 68.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is also worth noting that the experience of some minority ethnic communities suggests cultural change is also important. Bangladeshi students used to per</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">form relatively poorly in schools. Now they out-perform White British students overall, and 56% of Bangladeshi students eligible for free school meals – including 53% of FSM boys – reach the five GCSE benchmark. That change may reflect community’s desire t</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o learn, backed by parents and teachers working to meet that desire.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It may also reflect the particular improvements made in London boroughs where many of the Bangladeshi population live.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> On overall performance, only traveller boys perform worse now at GCS</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E than White British students. 33% of Black Caribbean boys, for example, now reach the 5 GCSE standard (though overall White British students perform ten points better than Black Caribbean students)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">Whether the problem is significantly worse for white </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">working class boys than girls</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TABLE 3: </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Attainment gap by </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">gender</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Narrow'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> at Key Stage 2</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:418.2pt"><tr style="height:12.75pt"><td colspan="7" style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; bord