t 0pt 71.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recent exam data bears out both the gender and socio-economic gaps. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2012 Key Stage Test data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> suggest that 60% of White British boys eligible for free school meals reach level 2 in English and Maths, compared with 67% of White British FSM girls. This is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> larger than the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">four-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">point gender gap among all other pupils. However, there is a six-point gender gap across all FSM pupils. The big difference is in English</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> exam results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, where the gender gap among FSM pupils is 12 points</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#002060; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the main 5 GCSE indicator</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (including English and Maths), 27% of White British FSM boys reached this standard compared with 35% of girls, a slightly smaller gender gap than exists for all other pupils, but one consistent with the gap at age eleven. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">What steps schools can take to i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">mprove the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We believe that schools should focus in three specific areas to raise the attainment of pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Improving teaching; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Providing targeted interventions at key points; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Engaging parents and wider communities.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Improving Teaching</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Teaching can be improved by focusing on areas which have been shown to be most effective, on average, in meta-analyses and systematic reviews of e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ducational research.  The Sutton Trust-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EEF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Teaching and Learning Toolkit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a synthesis of over 8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">000 research studies and identifies, for example, that improving the quality of feedback provided to pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can lead to an average impact on learning of 8 additional months over the course of a year. </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Other high impact teaching strategies include the use of collaborative learning and the development of meta-cognitive skills, which teach pupils to plan, monitor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and evaluate their work.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">According to the National Foundation for Education Research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (NFER)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, 67 per cent of school leaders – up from 52 per cent last year – said their school now consults research in deciding their pupil premium priorities. Two fifths (43</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> per cent) of school leaders whose schools consider research evidence use the Sutton Trust/EEF Toolkit. Amongst all school leaders completing the survey, a third (36 per cent) said their school now uses the Toolkit.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The greater use of research to inform t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eaching strategies should be further encouraged.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sutton Trust research published in 2013 suggested that teachers can be improved through effective evaluation and appraisal. Drawing on evidence from the UK and US, in particular, the report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Testing Teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by Richard Murphy of the London School of Economics concluded that an effective evaluation system required the right mix of value-added performance data, classroom observation and student surveys.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Teaching is also the EEF’s biggest single focus for investment through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">grant-making.  For example within this strand of funding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the EEF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> awarded £543,000 to the Edge Hill University in March 2013 to evaluate the impact of lesson study, a process of impr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oving teaching practice that originated in Japan and involves teachers planning and observing lessons together.  It is being tested i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n 80 schools across the country.  The results from this train and others will support schools to take an evidence-based app</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roach to improving teaching.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Targeted interventions</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Targeted interventions at key points can help pupils who fall behind catch up with their peers, or act as preventative measures supporting students at risk of doing so.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is strong evidence of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e value and impact of early years intervention, as summarised in the Toolkit and elsewhere.  The EEF is also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> evaluating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a number of early years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> programmes, focusing in particular on early language development.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A second key point of intervention may be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the transition from primary to secondary school. Pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds are 16 percentage points less likely to have reached the expected level in English and Math</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s at the end of primary school.  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he challenge of moving to secondary school i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">compounded by the likelihood of summer “learning loss”, where pupils regress academically over the summer holidays.  Evidence from the United States suggests that pupils from disadvantaged backgrounds lose three months learning over the summer, compared </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to a single months for other pupils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2012, the EEF was awarded £10million </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the Department for Education t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o fund a Literacy Catch-up round to find out the most effective interventions to support pupils who did not achieve Level 4 in English at the e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd of primary school, and the result from this round will be reporting in October 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Engaging parents and communities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Evidence summarised in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Toolkit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suggests that higher parental engagement is related with better attainment outcomes, but that incr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">easing low parental engagement is challenging.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The EEF is funding a number of programmes which seek to do this, including the Plymouth Parent Partnership, which provides parents with the skills they need to help their child learn to read.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The OECD has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also shown that the generally low levels of skills of NEETs erode very rapidly so that after a few years they become unemployable.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As a country we simply cannot afford to waste talent and the economic inactivity which results is simply unacceptable.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">potential for a wider range of educational approaches, for example vocational pathways, to improve outcomes for white working class pupils</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">NEET statistics</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 935,000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> young people aged 16-24 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not in education, employment or training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (often referred to as NEETs).</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Young people with poor educational attainment are much more likely to end up in this group.  Data from the OECD shows that those in the UK aged between 15 and 29 spend an average of 2.3 years unemployed or out of the labour </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">market entirely, a figure which is higher than the European Union average</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Office of National Statistics figures shows that students who leave school without 5A*-C including English and Maths have a greatly increased risk of becoming NEET and of remainin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g NEET for a long period of time</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> . For this reason we believe that a focus on academic attainment is important.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Sutton Trust has also been working with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">BCG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to analyse the vocational opportunities available to young people in England compared with oth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er countries such as Germany, Switzerland, Singapore and Australia, and will be publishing evidence in autumn 2013 on the differential availability of dual track vocational and professional education in different countries, and making recommendations for t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he UK, which we believe should provide many more opportunities with a strong work-based element.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Strong high quality apprenticeships should be much more widely available to young people in England.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">What role Government can play in delivering improved educ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">ational outcomes for white working class pupils</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Pupil Premium and the use of evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Pupil Premium was introduced in 2010 to provide extra resources to schools with disadvantaged intakes.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2013/14 the Pupil Premium is worth £900 per eligible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">student.  Disadvantaged pupils are pupils that have been recorded as eligible for free school meals (FSM) at any point in the last six years (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">known as “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ever 6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> FSM) or pupils in care who have been continuously looked after for more than six months by the l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal authority.  In total the Premium is worth £1.875 billion in 2013/14.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On average, schools receive £83,000 from the Premium, though some schools receive much more.  More than 5,200 schools, both primary and secondary currently receive over £100,000 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">om the Premium.  The Premium is worth £57,368 on average for primaries and £207,000 for secondaries.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The IFS estimates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Schools also already have significant funds for disadvantaged pupils additional to the premium, according to the Institute for Fiscal Stu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dies.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This can be worth £2000 per FSM pupil in primaries and £3000 in secondaries.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 71.66pt; padding-left:0.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Polling of teachers by NFER for the Sutton Trust </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s shown</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">upil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remium may not be being spent in ways which will maximise its impact on attainment.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lthough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> schools are considering research evidence, they are not yet embracing two measures seen as the most cost-effective interventions in the Toolkit. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 71.66pt; padding-left:0.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The NFER polling showed that only 4 per cent of teachers would spend the money first on improving feedback b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etween teachers and pupils, a relatively inexpensive measure that could add eight months to pupils’ learning. Improving feedback is an important way to improve teacher development.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">And only 1 per cent would use peer-to-peer tutoring schemes, where older pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pils typically help younger pupils to learn, an equally cost-effective measure that has proven six month learning gains.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">crucial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tool which schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> use to inform their decision making can ensure that they identify the “best bets” for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spending, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it must be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> acted upon.  The EEF’s own qualitative research is consistent with this view.  Even where money is spent on strategies which research shows have not always been effective (e.g. on teaching assistants), evidence can help schools ide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntify steps which make success more likely.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The success of the Pupil Premium as a policy and, as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remium is a key lever being used to raise the attainment of disadvantaged pupils, by extension the degree to which the system as a whole is likely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">succeed at narrowing the attainment gap between disadvantaged pupils and their peers will depend on the degree to which it is spent effectively.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To increase the likelihood of effective spending teachers need to be provided with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> research and the skill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s to use it.  Resources such as the Sutton Trust-EEF Teaching and Learning Toolkit provide a good entry point to research, but more could be through initial teacher training and professional development to equip teachers with the skills to engage with and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">approach research and to foster an understanding of the ways in which research can be use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The opportunities to innovate which exist in a system with increasing autonomy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> increase the importance of evidence.  In particular, schools should be supported to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evaluate innovation robustly, and challenged to ensure that innovation is based in sound pedagogy and existing research. In addition, where new school networks and structures exist these should be designed in such a way that increases the spread of knowled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ge to other schools, so that greater autonomy does not lead to increased isolation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government should also consider linking some of the pupil premium to school rewards, so that schools that successfully and consistently improve results for all while narro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wing the attainment gap are properly recognised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-variant:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.suttontrust.com/our-work/research/item/premium-policies/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.suttontrust.com/our-work/research/item/premium-policies/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2012 Key Stage Test data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  at </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-in-england-academic-year-2011-to-2012"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-in-england-academic-year-2011-to-2012</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://educationendowmentfoundation.org.uk/toolkit"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://educationendowmentfoundation.org.uk/toolkit</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href=